Introduction and Data Summary

Introduction

Our group is interested in exploring the cash use as transit fare payment method in the Greater Seattle area.

The research is drawn from the assumption that the paying transit fare in cash decreases the efficiency of the transportation system. Cash is not efficient as payment method for both riders and transport service providers. From the riders’ perspective, everytime the rider uses cash, they need to have exact amount of money to pay at the entrance, which definitely adds some complexity for some riders. From the service provider’s perspetive, using cash increases the wait time and can cause delays in the schedule.

Sound transit requested this research to find out to what extent cash is still used in the Greater Seattle area. They would be also interested what population will be more likely to use cash for transit fare payment.


Research Question

The main research question is the following:

Whether cash has a big stake in transit fare payment methods among riders in the Greater Seattle area and if so, who are most likely to pay transit fare in cash?


Data

The data we use for the research is the Seattle Sound Transit Survey Data, collected on different Sound Transit routes during October-November 2015. The full original dataset contains 134 variables and 3398 observations.

Our variable of interest is fare type (named as “faretype”), which means what method of payment was used by a rider to pay a transit fare. Later, we transform this variable into the dummy variable with the values (Cash/Not Cash), which we further use as the dependent variable for the regressin analysis to assess the impact of chosen explanatory variables on the likelihood of using cash as the transit fare payment method.

The independent variables we used for the research include:

  • Purpose of the trip (“purpose”)
  • Household Income (“income”)
  • Vehicle in the household (“vehicle”)
  • Number of trips made on any transit route in the region in the last month (“number_of_trips”)

The dataset has a lot of missing values. For the purpose of this research, we drop the whole observation if there is a missing value in one of the variables of interests.

We noticed that some values of income are not consistent. Therefore, we unify the format of the values by recoding them. Additionally, we regrouping income levels to 4 groups: lowest, medium-low, medium-high, and highest income.

#the category of income need some work
linkdata <- linkdata %>% mutate(income = recode(income, 
                                    "16,000-$19,999"="$16,000-$19,999",
                                    "12000-15999" ="$12,000-$15,999",
                                    "Under 12000"="Under $12,000")) 
#regroup income levels based on Seattle 2015 Household Income Quantile, https://www.kingcounty.gov/independent/forecasting/King%20County%20Economic%20Indicators/Household%20Income/KC%20Household%20Income%20Quintiles.aspx
lowest_income <- c("Under $12000","$12,000-$15,999", "$16,000-$19,999", "$20,000-$23,999", "$24,000-$31,999", "$32,000-$39,999")
medium_low_income <- c("$40,000-$48,999", "$57,000-$74,999", "$49,000-$56,999")
medium_high_income <-c("$75,000-$99,999")
highest_income <- c("$100,000+")

linkdata <- linkdata %>% mutate(income = case_when(
  income %in% lowest_income~"lowest",
  income %in% medium_low_income~"medium_low",
  income %in% medium_high_income~"medium_high",
  income %in% highest_income~"highest"))

To answer this question, we can build a univariate plot, showing the proportions of use of certain types of payment methods.

To build plots, we will use ggplot2 package. This packege will build plot based on the data frame. So before building the plot, we need to create the data frame of relative values lets finalizing the data frame for univariable ggplot**

We will need to separate data we are interested to analyze (subsetting the data), and calculate the frequences

Regression Analysis

Question 3: What’s the impact of explanatory variables on cash usage?

In this section, we will explore the realationship among the probability of using cash for this trip, whether people have vehicles, the purpose of this trip, and frequency of using public transportation.

Doing Regression with logit model

Here we use logit model since our dependent variable is a binary variable. Our reference group is people who has lowest income, whose purpose of this trip is home-based non-work trip and don’t have vehicles at home.

mydata2 <- within(mydata2, income <- relevel(income, ref = "lowest"))
mydata2 <- within(mydata2, purpose <- relevel(purpose, ref = "Home Based Non-Work Trip"))
library(dotwhisker)
library(broom)
#just use purpose as explantary variable
mylogit1 <- glm(cashlove ~ purpose, data = mydata2, family = "binomial")
model1 = tidy(mylogit1) %>%   # we save the result as a tidy object and...
    mutate(model = "Model 1")
#use 
mylogit2 <- glm(cashlove ~ purpose + vehicle, data = mydata2, family = "binomial")
model2 = tidy(mylogit2) %>%   # we save the result as a tidy object and...
    mutate(model = "Model 2")
#use 
mylogit3 <- glm(cashlove ~ purpose + vehicle +number_of_trips, data = mydata2, family = "binomial")
model3 = tidy(mylogit3) %>%   # we save the result as a tidy object and...
    mutate(model = "Model 3")
#use 
mylogit4 <- glm(cashlove ~ purpose + vehicle + number_of_trips + income, data = mydata2, family = "binomial")
model4 = tidy(mylogit4) %>%   # we save the result as a tidy object and...
    mutate(model = "Model 4")
summary(mylogit4)

Comparing four models

allModels=rbind(model1, model2, model3, model4)

dwplot(allModels, vline = geom_vline(xintercept = 0, colour = "grey60", linetype = 2)) + 
  xlab("Coefficient Estimate") + 
  ylab("") +
  ggtitle("Predicting probability of using cash") +
  theme_bw()

From the plot above, we can see that compared with reference group, people in the highest income group are less likely to use cash, people whose purpose is home based work trip have less probability using cash, while people whose purpose is non-home based trip is more likely to use cash. The more trips people have in each month, the less likelihood people would use cash. However, the difference on cash usage between people who have vehicles in home and people who don’t is not significant.
